{"key":"processedPost-6092602","value":{"id":6092602,"first":6092444,"last":6092881,"when":1159017872,"utime":"09/23/06 04:24 PM","cleanedPost":"The temperature of the entire content of the jars will not equalize to the tub temperature.  <br />Colonizing mycelium generates heat, so the inside of the jars will be 2 to 5 degrees warmer than the air they sit in, meaning an 86F incubator can easily have 90F jars sitting in it, which is too much and favors contaminants such as thermophilic bacteria.<br />80 to 83F should be considered maximum temperature for colonizing.  Personally, I colonize jars on an open shelf at normal room temperature.<br />RR"}}